# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-spanner
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Consistency models are used in distributed systems like distributed shared memory systems or distributed data stores (such as filesystems, databases, optimistic replication systems or web caching).
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Consistency is different from coherence, which occurs in systems that are cached or cache-less, and is consistency of data with respect to all processors.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Coherence deals with maintaining a global order in which writes to a single location or single variable are seen by all processors.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Consistency deals with the ordering of operations to multiple locations with respect to all processors.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The consistency model determines whether client B will definitely see the write performed by client A, will definitely not, or cannot depend on seeing the write.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Consistency models define rules for the apparent order and visibility of updates, and are on a continuum with tradeoffs.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] There are two methods to define and categorize consistency models; issue and view.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Issue method describes the restrictions that define how a process can issue operations.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] For example, a consistency model can define that a process is not allowed to issue an operation until all previously issued operations are completed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Different consistency models enforce different conditions.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] One consistency model can be considered stronger than another if it requires all conditions of that model and more.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In other words, a model with fewer constraints is considered a weaker consistency model.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] These models define how the hardware needs to be laid out and at a high-level, how the programmer must code.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The chosen model also affects how the compiler can re-order instructions.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Generally, if control dependencies between instructions and if writes to same location are ordered, then the compiler can reorder as required.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] However, with the models described below, some may allow writes before loads to be reordered while some may not.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Strict consistency is the strongest consistency model.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Under this model, a write to a variable by any processor needs to be seen instantaneously by all processors.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The strict model diagram and non-strict model diagrams describe the time constraint – instantaneous.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] It can be better understood as though a global clock is present in which every write should be reflected in all processor caches by the end of that clock period.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The next operation must happen only in the next clock period.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In the following diagram, P means "process" and the global clock's value is represented in the Sequence column.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In this model, the programmer's expected result will be received every time.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Its practical relevance is restricted to a thought experiment and formalism, because instantaneous message exchange is impossible.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] It doesn't help in answering the question of conflict resolution in concurrent writes to the same data item, because it assumes concurrent writes to be impossible.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The sequential consistency model was proposed by Lamport (1979).
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] It is a weaker memory model than strict consistency model.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A write to a variable does not have to be seen instantaneously, however, writes to variables by different processors have to be seen in the same order by all processors.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In sequential consistency, there is no notion of time or most recent write operations.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] There are some operations interleaving that is the same for all processes.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A process can see the write operations of all processes but it can just see its own read operations.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Program order within each processor and sequential ordering of operations between processors should be maintained.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In order to preserve sequential order of execution between processors, all operations must appear to execute instantaneously or atomically with respect to every other processor.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] These operations need only "appear" to be completed because it is physically impossible to send information instantaneously.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] For instance, in a system utilizing a single globally shared bus, once a bus line is posted with information, it is guaranteed that all processors will see the information at the same instant.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Thus, passing the information to the bus line completes the execution with respect to all processors and has appeared to have been executed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Cache-less architectures or cached architectures with interconnect networks that are not instantaneous can contain a slow path between processors and memories.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] These slow paths can result in sequential inconsistency, because some memories receive the broadcast data faster than others.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Sequential consistency can produce non-deterministic results.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This is because the sequence of sequential operations between processors can be different during different runs of the program.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] All memory operations need to happen in the program order.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Linearizability (also known as atomic consistency or atomic memory) can be defined as sequential consistency with a real-time constraint, by considering a begin time and end time for each operation.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] An execution is linearizable if each operation taking place in linearizable order by placing a point between its begin time and its end time and guarantees sequential consistency.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Verifying sequential consistency through model checking is undecidable in general, even for finite-state cache coherence protocols.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Causal consistency defined by Hutto and Ahamad, 1990, is a weakening of the sequential consistency model by categorizing events into those causally related and those that are not.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] It defines that only write operations that are causally related, need to be seen in the same order by all processes.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] For example, if an event b takes effect from an earlier event a, the causal consistency guarantees that all processes see event b after event a.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This model relaxes sequential consistency on concurrent writes by a processor and on writes that are not causally related.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Two writes can become causally related if one write to a variable is dependent on a previous write to any variable if the processor doing the second write has just read the first write.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The two writes could have been done by the same processor or by different processors.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] As in sequential consistency, reads do not need to reflect changes instantaneously, however, they need to reflect all changes to a variable sequentially.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] W(x)2 happens after W(x)1 due to the read made by P2 to x before W(x)2, hence this example is *causally consistent* under Hutto and Ahamad's definition (although not under Tanenbaum et al.'s, because W(x)2 and W(x)3 are not seen in the same order for all processes).
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] However R(x)2 and R(x)3 happen in a different order on P3 and P4, hence this example is *sequentially inconsistent*.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In order for consistency in data to be maintained and to attain scalable processor systems where every processor has its own memory, the processor consistency model was derived.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] All processors need to be consistent in the order in which they see writes done by one processor and in the way they see writes by different processors to the same location (coherence is maintained).
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] However, they do not need to be consistent when the writes are by different processors to different locations.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Every write operation can be divided into several sub-writes to all memories.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A read from one such memory can happen before the write to this memory completes.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Thus, a processor under PC can execute a younger load when an older store needs to be stalled.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Read before write, read after read and write before write ordering is still preserved in this model.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The processor consistency model is similar to the PRAM consistency model with a stronger condition that defines all writes to the same memory location must be seen in the same sequential order by all other processes.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Processor consistency is weaker than sequential consistency but stronger than the PRAM consistency model.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The Stanford DASH multiprocessor system implements a variation of processor consistency which is incomparable (neither weaker nor stronger) to Goodman's definitions.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] All processors need to be consistent in the order in which they see writes by one processor and in the way they see writes by different processors to the same location.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Pipelined RAM consistency (PRAM consistency) was presented by Lipton and Sandberg in 1988 as one of the first described consistency models.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Due to its informal definition, there are in fact at least two subtly different implementations, one by Ahamad et al. and one by Mosberger.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In PRAM consistency, all processes view the operations of a single process in the same order that they were issued by that process, while operations issued by different processes can be viewed in different order from different processes.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] PRAM consistency is weaker than processor consistency.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] PRAM relaxes the need to maintain coherence to a location across all its processors.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Here, reads to any variable can be executed before writes in a processor.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Cache consistency requires that all write operations to the same memory location are performed in some sequential order.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Cache consistency is weaker than processor consistency and incomparable with PRAM consistency.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In slow consistency, if a process reads a value previously written to a memory location, it cannot subsequently read any earlier value from that location.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Writes performed by a process are immediately visible to that process.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Slow consistency is a weaker model than PRAM and cache consistency.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Hutto, Phillip W., and Mustaque Ahamad (1990) illustrate that by appropriate programming, slow memory (consistency) can be expressive and efficient.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] They mention that slow memory has two valuable properties; locality and supporting reduction from atomic memory.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] They propose two algorithms to present the expressiveness of slow memory.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] These 4 consistency models were proposed in a 1994 paper.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] They focus on guarantees in the situation where only a single user or application is making data modifications.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] If a process reads the value of a data item x, any successive read operation on x by that process will always return that same value or a more recent value.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A write operation by a process on a data item X is completed before any successive write operation on X by the same process.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A value written by a process on a data item X will always be available to a successive read operation performed by the same process on data item X.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A write operation by a process on a data item x following a previous read operation on x by the same process is guaranteed to take place on the same or a more recent value of x that was read.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The following models require specific synchronization by programmers.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Weak ordering classifies memory operations into two categories: *data operations* and *synchronization operations*.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] To enforce program order, a programmer needs to find at least one synchronisation operation in a program.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Synchronization operations signal the processor to make sure it has completed and seen all previous operations done by all processors.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Program order and atomicity is maintained only on synchronisation operations and not on all reads and writes.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This was derived from the understanding that certain memory operations – such as those conducted in a critical section - need not be seen by all processors until after all operations in the critical section are completed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] It assumes reordering memory operations to data regions between synchronisation operations does not affect the outcome of the program.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This exploits the fact that programs written to be executed on a multi-processor system contain the required synchronization to make sure that data races do not occur and SC outcomes are produced always.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Once these requirements are met, all other "data" operations can be reordered.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The way this works is that a counter tracks the number of data operations and until this counter becomes zero, the synchronisation operation isn't issued.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Furthermore, no more data operations are issued unless all the previous synchronisations are completed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Memory operations in between two synchronisation variables can be overlapped and reordered without affecting the correctness of the program.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This model ensures that write atomicity is always maintained, therefore no additional safety net is required for weak ordering.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In order to maintain weak ordering, write operations prior to a synchronization operation must be globally performed before the synchronization operation.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Operations present after a synchronization operation should also be performed only after the synchronization operation completes.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Therefore, accesses to synchronization variables is sequentially consistent and any read or write should be performed only after previous synchronization operations have completed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] There is high reliance on explicit synchronization in the program.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] For weak ordering models, the programmer must use atomic locking instructions such as test-and-set, fetch-and-op, store conditional, load linked or must label synchronization variables or use fences.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The release consistency model relaxes the weak consistency model by distinguishing the entrance synchronization operation from the exit synchronization operation.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Under weak ordering, when a synchronization operation is to be seen, all operations in all processors need to be visible before the synchronization operation is done and the processor proceeds.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] However, under the release consistency model, during the entry to a critical section, termed as "acquire", all operations with respect to the local memory variables need to be completed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] During the exit, termed as "release", all changes made by the local processor should be propagated to all other processors.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The acquire operation is a load/read that is performed to access the critical section.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A release operation is a store/write performed to allow other processors to use the shared variables.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Among synchronization variables, sequential consistency or processor consistency can be maintained.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Using SC, all competing synchronization variables should be processed in order.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] However, with PC, a pair of competing variables need to only follow this order.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Younger acquires can be allowed to happen before older releases.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] There are two types of release consistency, release consistency with sequential consistency (RCsc) and release consistency with processor consistency (RCpc).
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The latter type denotes which type of consistency is applied to those operations nominated below as special.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] There are special (cf. ordinary) memory operations, themselves consisting of two classes of operations: *sync* or *nsync* operations.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The latter are operations not used for synchronisation; the former are, and consist of *acquire* and *release* operations.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] An acquire is effectively a read memory operation used to obtain access to a certain set of shared locations.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Release, on the other hand, is a write operation that is performed for granting permission to access the shared locations.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Note: the above notation A → B, implies that if the operation A precedes B in the program order, then program order is enforced.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This is a variant of the release consistency model.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] It also requires the use of *acquire* and *release* instructions to explicitly state an entry or exit to a critical section.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] However, under entry consistency, every shared variable is assigned a synchronization variable specific to it.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This way, only when the acquire is to variable x, all operations related to x need to be completed with respect to that processor.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This allows concurrent operations of different critical sections of different shared variables to occur.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Concurrency cannot be seen for critical operations on the same shared variable.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Such a consistency model will be useful when different matrix elements can be processed at the same time.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In local consistency, each process performs its own operations in the order defined by its program.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] There is no constraint on the ordering in which the write operations of other processes appear to be performed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Local consistency is the weakest consistency model in shared memory systems.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In general consistency, all the copies of a memory location are eventually identical after all processes' writes are completed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] An eventual consistency is a weak consistency model in a system with the lack of simultaneous updates.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] It defines that if no update takes a very long time, all replicas eventually become consistent.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Some different consistency models can be defined by relaxing one or more requirements in sequential consistency called relaxed consistency models.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] These consistency models do not provide memory consistency at the hardware level.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In fact, the programmers are responsible for implementing the memory consistency by applying synchronization techniques.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The above models are classified based on four criteria and are detailed further.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] One way to categorize the relaxed consistency is to define which sequential consistency requirements are relaxed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] We can have less strict models by relaxing either program order or write atomicity requirements defined by Adve and Gharachorloo, 1996.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Program order guarantees that each process issues a memory request ordered by its program and write atomicity defines that memory requests are serviced based on the order of a single FIFO queue.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In relaxing program order, any or all the ordering of operation pairs, write-after-write, read-after-write, or read/write-after-read, can be relaxed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In the relaxed write atomicity model, a process can view its own writes before any other processors.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A synchronizing model can be defined by dividing the memory accesses into two groups and assigning different consistency restrictions to each group considering that one group can have a weak consistency model while the other one needs a more restrictive consistency model.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In contrast, a non-synchronizing model assigns the same consistency model to the memory access types.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Issue method provides sequential consistency simulation by defining the restrictions for processes to issue memory operations.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Whereas, view method describes the visibility restrictions on the events order for processes.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Some consistency models are more restrictive than others.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In other words, strict consistency models enforce more constraints as consistency requirements.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The strength of a model can be defined by the program order or atomicity relaxations and the strength of models can also be compared.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Some models are directly related if they apply the same relaxations or more.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] On the other hand, the models that relax different requirements are not directly related.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Sequential consistency has two requirements, program order and write atomicity.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Different relaxed consistency models can be obtained by relaxing these requirements.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This is done so that, along with relaxed constraints, the performance increases, but the programmer is responsible for implementing the memory consistency by applying synchronisation techniques and must have a good understanding of the hardware.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] An approach to improving the performance at the hardware level is by relaxing the PO of a write followed by a read which effectively hides the latency of write operations.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The optimisation this type of relaxation relies on is that it allows the subsequent reads to be in a relaxed order with respect to the previous writes from the processor.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Because of this relaxation some programs like XXX may fail to give SC results because of this relaxation.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Whereas, programs like YYY are still expected to give consistent results because of the enforcement of the remaining program order constraints.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The IBM 370 model is the strictest model.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A read can be complete before an earlier write to a different address, but it is prohibited from returning the value of the write unless all the processors have seen the write.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The SPARC V8 total store ordering model (TSO) model partially relaxes the IBM 370 Model, it allows a read to return the value of its own processor's write with respect to other writes to the same location i.e. it returns the value of its own write before others see it.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Similar to the previous model, this cannot return the value of write unless all the processors have seen the write.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The processor consistency model (PC) is the most relaxed of the three models and relaxes both the constraints such that a read can complete before an earlier write even before it is made visible to other processors.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In Example A, the result is possible only in IBM 370 because read(A) is not issued until the write(A) in that processor is completed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] On the other hand, this result is possible in TSO and PC because they allow the reads of the flags before the writes of the flags in a single processor.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In Example B the result is possible only with PC as it allows P2 to return the value of a write even before it is visible to P3.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This won't be possible in the other two models.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] To ensure sequential consistency in the above models, safety nets or fences are used to manually enforce the constraint.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The IBM370 model has some specialised *serialisation instructions* which are manually placed between operations.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] These instructions can consist of memory instructions or non-memory instructions such as branches.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] On the other hand, the TSO and PC models do not provide safety nets, but the programmers can still use read-modify-write operations to make it appear like the program order is still maintained between a write and a following read.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In case of TSO, PO appears to be maintained if the R or W which is already a part of a R-modify-W is replaced by a R-modify-W, this requires the W in the R-modify-W is a ‘dummy’ that returns the read value.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Similarly for PC, PO seems to be maintained if the read is replaced by a write or is already a part of R-modify-W.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] However, compiler optimisations cannot be done after exercising this relaxation alone.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Compiler optimisations require the full flexibility of reordering any two operations in the PO, so the ability to reorder a write with respect to a read is not sufficiently helpful in this case.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Some models relax the program order even further by relaxing even the ordering constraints between writes to different locations.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The SPARC V8 partial store ordering model (PSO) is the only example of such a model.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The ability to pipeline and overlap writes to different locations from the same processor is the key hardware optimisation enabled by PSO.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] PSO is similar to TSO in terms of atomicity requirements, in that it allows a processor to read the value of its own write and prevents other processors from reading another processor's write before the write is visible to all other processors.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Program order between two writes is maintained by PSO using an explicit STBAR instruction.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The STBAR is inserted in a write buffer in implementations with FIFO write buffers.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A counter is used to determine when all the writes before the STBAR instruction have been completed, which triggers a write to the memory system to increment the counter.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A write acknowledgement decrements the counter, and when the counter becomes 0, it signifies that all the previous writes are completed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In the examples A and B, PSO allows both these non-sequentially consistent results.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The safety net that PSO provides is similar to TSO's, it imposes program order from a write to a read and enforces write atomicity.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Similar to the previous models, the relaxations allowed by PSO are not sufficiently flexible to be useful for compiler optimisation, which requires a much more flexible optimisation.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In some models, all operations to different locations are relaxed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A read or write may be reordered with respect to a different read or write in a different location.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The *weak ordering* may be classified under this category and two types of release consistency models (RCsc and RCpc) also come under this model.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Three commercial architectures are also proposed under this category of relaxation: the Digital Alpha, SPARC V9 relaxed memory order (RMO), and IBM PowerPC models.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] These three commercial architectures exhibit explicit fence instructions as their safety nets.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The Alpha model provides two types of fence instructions, *memory barrier* (MB) and *write memory barrier* (WMB).
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The MB operation can be used to maintain program order of any memory operation before the MB with a memory operation after the barrier.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Similarly, the WMB maintains program order only among writes.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The SPARC V9 RMO model provides a MEMBAR instruction which can be customised to order previous reads and writes with respect to future read and write operations.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] There is no need for using read-modify-writes to achieve this order because the MEMBAR instruction can be used to order a write with respect to a succeeding read.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The PowerPC model uses a single fence instruction called the SYNC instruction.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] It is similar to the MB instruction, but with a little exception that reads can occur out of program order even if a SYNC is placed between two reads to the same location.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This model also differs from Alpha and RMO in terms of atomicity.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] It allows a write to be seen earlier than a read's completion.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A combination of read modify write operations may be required to make an illusion of write atomicity.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] RMO and PowerPC allow reordering of reads to the same location.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] These models violate sequential order in examples A and B.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] An additional relaxation allowed in these models is that memory operations following a read operation can be overlapped and reordered with respect to the read.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Alpha and RMO allow a read to return the value of another processor's early write.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] From a programmer's perspective these models must maintain the illusion of write atomicity even though they allow the processor to read its own write early.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Transactional memory model is the combination of cache coherency and memory consistency models as a communication model for shared memory systems supported by software or hardware; a transactional memory model provides both memory consistency and cache coherency.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A transaction is a sequence of operations executed by a process that transforms data from one consistent state to another.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A transaction either commits when there is no conflict or aborts.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In commits, all changes are visible to all other processes when a transaction is completed, while aborts discard all changes.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Compared to relaxed consistency models, a transactional model is easier to use and can provide higher performance than a sequential consistency model.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Several other consistency models have been conceived to express restrictions with respect to ordering or visibility of operations, or to deal with specific fault assumptions.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Tanenbaum et al., 2007 defines two main reasons for replicating; reliability and performance.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Reliability can be achieved in a replicated file system by switching to another replica in the case of the current replica failure.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The replication also protects data from being corrupted by providing multiple copies of data on different replicas.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] It also improves the performance by dividing the work.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] While replication can improve performance and reliability, it can cause consistency problems between multiple copies of data.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The multiple copies are consistent if a read operation returns the same value from all copies and a write operation as a single atomic operation (transaction) updates all copies before any other operation takes place.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Tanenbaum, Andrew, & Maarten Van Steen, 2007 refer to this type of consistency as **tight consistency** provided by synchronous replication.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] However, applying global synchronizations to keep all copies consistent is costly.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] One way to decrease the cost of global synchronization and improve the performance can be weakening the consistency restrictions.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Tanenbaum et al., 2007 defines the **consistency model** as a contract between the software (processes) and memory implementation (data store).
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This model guarantees that if the software follows certain rules, the memory works correctly.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Since, in a system without a global clock, defining the last operation among writes is difficult, some restrictions can be applied on the values that can be returned by a read operation.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The goal of data-centric consistency models is to provide a consistent view on a data store where processes may carry out concurrent updates.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Some consistency models such as sequential and also causal consistency models deal with the order of operations on shared replicated data in order to provide consistency.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In these models, all replicas must agree on a consistent global ordering of updates.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In grouping operation, accesses to the synchronization variables are sequentially consistent.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A process is allowed to access a synchronization variable that all previous writes have been completed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In other words, accesses to synchronization variables are not permitted until all operations on the synchronization variables are completely performed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In distributed systems, maintaining sequential consistency in order to control the concurrent operations is essential.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In some special data stores without simultaneous updates, client-centric consistency models can deal with inconsistencies in a less costly way.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The implementation of a consistency model is defined by a consistency protocol.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Tanenbaum et al., 2007 illustrates some consistency protocols for data-centric models.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Continuous consistency introduced by Yu and Vahdat (2000).
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In this model, the consistency semantics of an application is described by using conits in the application.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Since the consistency requirements can differ based on application semantics, Yu and Vahdat (2000) believe that a predefined uniform consistency model may not be an appropriate approach.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The application should specify the consistency requirements that satisfy the application semantics.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In this model, an application specifies each consistency requirement as a conit (abbreviation of consistency units).
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A conit can be a physical or logical consistency and is used to measure the consistency.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Tanenbaum et al., 2007 describes the notion of a conit by giving an example.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] There are three inconsistencies that can be tolerated by applications.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Numerical deviation bounds the difference between the conit value and the relative value of the last update.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A weight can be assigned to the writes which defines the importance of the writes in a specific application.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The total weights of unseen writes for a conit can be defined as a numerical deviation in an application.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] There are two different types of numerical deviation; absolute and relative numerical deviation.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Ordering deviation is the discrepancy between the local order of writes in a replica and their relative ordering in the eventual final image.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Staleness deviation defines the validity of the oldest write by bounding the difference between the current time and the time of the oldest write on a conit not seen locally.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Each server has a local queue of uncertain write that is required an actual order to be determined and applied on a conit.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The maximal length of uncertain writes queue is the bound of ordering deviation.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] When the number of writes exceeds the limit, instead of accepting new submitted write, the server will attempt to commit uncertain writes by communicating with other servers based on the order that writes should be executed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] If all three deviation bounds are set to zero, the continuous consistency model is the strong consistency.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Primary-based protocols can be considered as a class of consistency protocols that are simpler to implement.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] For instance, sequential ordering is a popular consistency model when consistent ordering of operations is considered.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The sequential ordering can be determined as primary-based protocol.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In these protocols, there is an associated primary for each data item in a data store to coordinate write operations on that data item.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In the simplest primary-based protocol that supports replication, also known as primary-backup protocol, write operations are forwarded to a single server and read operations can be performed locally.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] gives an example of a primary-backup protocol.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The diagram of primary-backup protocol shows an example of this protocol.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] When a client requests a write, the write request is forwarded to a primary server.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The primary server sends request to backups to perform the update.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The server then receives the update acknowledgement from all backups and sends the acknowledgement of completion of writes to the client.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Any client can read the last available update locally.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The trade-off of this protocol is that a client who sends the update request might have to wait so long to get the acknowledgement in order to continue.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This problem can be solved by performing the updates locally, and then asking other backups to perform their updates.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The non-blocking primary-backup protocol does not guarantee the consistency of update on all backup servers.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In the primary-backup protocol, all processes will see the same order of write operations since this protocol orders all incoming writes based on a globally unique time.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Blocking protocols guarantee that processes view the result of the last write operation.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In primary-based local-write protocols, primary copy moves between processes willing to perform an update.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] To update a data item, a process first moves it to its location.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] As a result, in this approach, successive write operations can be performed locally while each process can read their local copy of data items.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] After the primary finishes its update, the update is forwarded to other replicas and all perform the update locally.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] This non-blocking approach can lead to an improvement.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The diagram of the local-write protocol depicts the local-write approach in primary-based protocols.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A process requests a write operation in a data item x.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The current server is considered as the new primary for a data item x.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The write operation is performed and when the request is finished, the primary sends an update request to other backup servers.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Each backup sends an acknowledgment to the primary after finishing the update operation.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In replicated-write protocols, unlike the primary-based protocol, all updates are carried out to all replicas.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In active replication, there is a process associated with each replica to perform the write operation.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In other words, updates are sent to each replica in the form of an operation in order to be executed.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] All updates need to be performed in the same order in all replicas.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] As a result, a totally-ordered multicast mechanism is required.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] There is a scalability issue in implementing such a multicasting mechanism in large distributed systems.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] There is another approach in which each operation is sent to a central coordinator (sequencer).
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The coordinator first assigns a sequence number to each operation and then forwards the operation to all replicas.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Second approach cannot also solve the scalability problem.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Voting can be another approach in replicated-write protocols.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In this approach, a client requests and receives permission from multiple servers in order to read and write a replicated data.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] As an example, suppose in a distributed file system, a file is replicated on N servers.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] To update a file, a client must send a request to at least N/2 + 1 in order to make their agreement to perform an update.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] After the agreement, changes are applied on the file and a new version number is assigned to the updated file.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Similarly, for reading replicated file, a client sends a request to N/2 + 1 servers in order to receive the associated version number from those servers.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Read operation is completed if all received version numbers are the most recent version.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In a replicated file system, a cache-coherence protocol provides the cache consistency while caches are generally controlled by clients.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In many approaches, cache consistency is provided by the underlying hardware.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Some other approaches in middleware-based distributed systems apply software-based solutions to provide the cache consistency.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Cache consistency models can differ in their coherence detection strategies that define when inconsistencies occur.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] There are two approaches to detect the inconsistency; static and dynamic solutions.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In the static solution, a compiler determines which variables can cause the cache inconsistency.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] So, the compiler enforces an instruction in order to avoid the inconsistency problem.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In the dynamic solution, the server checks for inconsistencies at run time to control the consistency of the cached data that has changed after it was cached.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] The coherence enforcement strategy is another cache-coherence protocol.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] It defines *how* to provide the consistency in caches by using the copies located on the server.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] One way to keep the data consistent is to never cache the shared data.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] A server can keep the data and apply some consistency protocol such as primary-based protocols to ensure the consistency of shared data.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In this solution, only private data can be cached by clients.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In the case that shared data is cached, there are two approaches in order to enforce the cache coherence.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In the first approach, when a shared data is updated, the server forwards invalidation to all caches.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] In the second approach, an update is propagated.
[src:gcp-spanner/consistency-model] Most caching systems apply these two approaches or dynamically choose between them.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] A **distributed database** is a database in which data is stored across different physical locations.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] It may be stored in multiple computers located in the same physical location (e.g. a data centre); or maybe dispersed over a network of interconnected computers.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] Unlike parallel systems, in which the processors are tightly coupled and constitute a single database system, a distributed database system consists of loosely coupled sites that share no physical components.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] System administrators can distribute collections of data (e.g. in a database) across multiple physical locations.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] A distributed database can reside on organised network servers or decentralised independent computers on the Internet, on corporate intranets or extranets, or on other organisation networks.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] Because distributed databases store data across multiple computers, distributed databases may improve performance at end-user worksites by allowing transactions to be processed on many machines, instead of being limited to one.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] Two processes ensure that the distributed databases remain up-to-date and current: replication and duplication.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] Duplication, on the other hand, has less complexity.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] It identifies one database as a master and then duplicates that database.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] The duplication process is normally done at a set time after hours.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] This is to ensure that each distributed location has the same data.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] In the duplication process, users may change only the master database.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] This ensures that local data will not be overwritten.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] Both replication and duplication can keep the data current in all distributive locations.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] Besides distributed database replication and fragmentation, there are many other distributed database design technologies.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] For example, local autonomy, synchronous, and asynchronous distributed database technologies.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] The implementation of these technologies can and do depend on the needs of the business and the sensitivity/confidentiality of the data stored in the database and the price the business is willing to spend on ensuring data security, consistency and integrity.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] In the shared-memory and shared-disk architectures, the data is not partitioned, but it has to be in a shared-nothing architecture.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] Shared-disk architecture is more common for cloud databases than for on-premise.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] Historically, shared-nothing was the first architecture to be implemented on the cloud, before the advent of shared cloud storage made shared-disk possible.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] In practice, different layers of the database can have different architectures.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] It is now common to have a compute layer with a shared nothing architecture, and a storage layer with a shared disk architecture.
[src:gcp-spanner/distributed-database] This is for instance the case of Snowflake and AWS Aurora.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] Many enterprise systems that handle high-profile data (e.g., financial and order processing systems) are too large for conventional relational databases, but have transactional and consistency requirements that are not practical for NoSQL systems.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] The only options previously available for these organizations were to either purchase more powerful computers or to develop custom middleware that distributes requests over conventional DBMS.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] Both approaches feature high infrastructure costs and/or development costs.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] NewSQL systems attempt to reconcile the conflicts.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] The term was first used by 451 Group analyst Matthew Aslett in a 2011 research paper discussing the rise of a new generation of database management systems.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] One of the first NewSQL systems was the H-Store parallel database system.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] Typical applications are characterized by heavy OLTP transaction volumes.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] However, some support hybrid transactional/analytical processing (HTAP) applications.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] Such systems improve performance and scalability by omitting heavyweight recovery or concurrency control.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] The two common distinguishing features of NewSQL database solutions are that they support online scalability of NoSQL databases and the relational data model (including ACID consistency) using SQL as their primary interface.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] NewSQL systems adopt various internal architectures.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] Some systems employ a cluster of shared-nothing nodes, in which each node manages a subset of the data.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] They include components such as distributed concurrency control, flow control, and distributed query processing.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] The second category are optimized storage engines for SQL.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] These systems provide the same programming interface as SQL, but scale better than built-in engines.
[src:gcp-spanner/newsql] These systems automatically split databases across multiple nodes using Raft or Paxos consensus algorithm.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] A **partition** is a division of a logical database or its constituent elements into distinct independent parts.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Database partitioning refers to intentionally breaking a large database into smaller ones for scalability purposes, distinct from network partitions which are a type of network fault between nodes.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] In a partitioned database, each piece of data belongs to exactly one partition, effectively making each partition a small database of its own.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Database partitioning is normally done for manageability, performance or availability reasons, or for load balancing.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] It is popular in distributed database management systems, where each partition may be spread over multiple nodes, with users at the node performing local transactions on the partition.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] This increases performance for sites that have regular transactions involving certain views of data, whilst maintaining availability and security.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Partitioning enables distribution of datasets across multiple disks and query loads across multiple processors.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] For queries that operate on a single partition, each node executes queries independently on its local partition, enabling linear scaling of query throughput with additional nodes.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] More complex queries can be parallelized across multiple nodes, though this presents additional challenges.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Database partitioning emerged in the 1980s with systems like Teradata and NonStop SQL.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] The approach was later adopted by NoSQL databases and Hadoop-based data warehouses.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] While implementations vary between transactional and analytical workloads, the core principles of partitioning remain consistent across both use cases.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Partitioning is commonly implemented alongside replication, storing partition copies across multiple nodes.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Each record belongs to one partition but may exist on multiple nodes for fault tolerance.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] In leader-follower replication systems, nodes can simultaneously serve as leaders for some partitions and followers for others.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Partitioning aims to distribute data and query load evenly across nodes.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] With ideal distribution, system capacity scales linearly with added nodes—ten nodes should process ten times the data and throughput of a single node.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Uneven distribution, termed *skew*, reduces partitioning efficiency.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Partitions with excessive load are called *hot spots*.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Current high-end relational database management systems provide for different criteria to split the database.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] They take a *partitioning key* and assign a partition based on certain criteria.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] In any partitioning scheme, data is typically arranged so that each piece of data (record, row, or document) belongs to exactly one partition.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] While some databases support operations that span multiple partitions, this single-partition association is fundamental to the partitioning concept.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] The partitioning can be done by either building separate smaller databases (each with its own tables, indices, and transaction logs), or by splitting selected elements, for example just one table.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Horizontal partitioning involves putting different rows into different tables.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] For example, customers with ZIP codes less than 50000 are stored in CustomersEast, while customers with ZIP codes greater than or equal to 50000 are stored in CustomersWest.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] The two partition tables are then CustomersEast and CustomersWest, while a view with a union might be created over both of them to provide a complete view of all customers.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Vertical partitioning involves creating tables with fewer columns and using additional tables to store the remaining columns.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Generally, this practice is known as normalization.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] However, vertical partitioning extends further, and partitions columns even when already normalized.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] This type of partitioning is also called "row splitting", since rows get split by their columns, and might be performed explicitly or implicitly.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Distinct physical machines might be used to realize vertical partitioning: storing infrequently used or very wide columns, taking up a significant amount of memory, on a different machine, for example, is a method of vertical partitioning.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] A common form of vertical partitioning is to split static data from dynamic data, since the former is faster to access than the latter, particularly for a table where the dynamic data is not used as often as the static.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] Creating a view across the two newly created tables restores the original table with a performance penalty, but accessing the static data alone will show higher performance.
[src:gcp-spanner/partition-database] A columnar database can be regarded as a database that has been vertically partitioned until each column is stored in its own table.
[src:gcp-spanner/spanner-database] Spanner stores large amounts of mutable structured data.
[src:gcp-spanner/spanner-database] Spanner allows users to perform arbitrary queries using SQL with relational data while maintaining strong consistency and high availability for that data with synchronous replication.
[src:gcp-spanner/spanner-database] Spanner was first described in 2012 for internal Google data centers.
[src:gcp-spanner/spanner-database] Spanner's SQL capability was added in 2017 and documented in a SIGMOD 2017 paper.
[src:gcp-spanner/spanner-database] It became available as part of Google Cloud Platform in 2017, under the name "Cloud Spanner".
[src:gcp-spanner/spanner-database] Spanner uses the Paxos algorithm as part of its operation to shard (partition) data across up to hundreds of servers.
[src:gcp-spanner/spanner-database] It makes heavy use of hardware-assisted clock synchronization using GPS clocks and atomic clocks to ensure global consistency.
[src:gcp-spanner/spanner-database] TrueTime is the brand name for Google's distributed cloud infrastructure, which provides Spanner with the ability to generate monotonically increasing timestamps in data centers around the world.
[src:gcp-spanner/spanner-database] Google's F1 SQL database management system (DBMS) is built on top of Spanner, replacing Google's custom MySQL variant.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] In transaction processing, databases, and computer networking, the **two-phase commit protocol** (**2PC**, *tupac*) is a type of atomic commitment protocol (ACP).
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] It is a distributed algorithm that coordinates all the processes that participate in a distributed atomic transaction on whether to commit or abort (roll back) the transaction.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] This protocol (a specialised type of consensus protocol) achieves its goal even in many cases of temporary system failure (involving either process, network node, communication, etc. failures), and is thus widely used.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] However, it is not resilient to all possible failure configurations, and in rare cases, manual intervention is needed to remedy an outcome.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] To accommodate recovery from failure (automatic in most cases) the protocol's participants use logging of the protocol's states.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Log records, which are typically slow to generate but survive failures, are used by the protocol's recovery procedures.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Many protocol variants exist that primarily differ in logging strategies and recovery mechanisms.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Though usually intended to be used infrequently, recovery procedures compose a substantial portion of the protocol, due to many possible failure scenarios to be considered and supported by the protocol.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The commit phase, in which, based on voting of the participants, the coordinator decides whether to commit (only if all have voted "Yes") or abort the transaction (otherwise), and notifies the result to all the participants.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The participants then follow with the needed actions (commit or abort) with their local transactional resources (also called recoverable resources; e.g., database data) and their respective portions in the transaction's other output (if applicable).
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The two-phase commit (2PC) protocol should not be confused with the two-phase locking (2PL) protocol, a concurrency control protocol.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The protocol works in the following manner: one node is a designated coordinator, which is the master site, and the rest of the nodes in the network are designated the participants.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] 4. any two nodes can communicate with each other.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The last assumption is not too restrictive, as network communication can typically be rerouted.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The first two assumptions are much stronger; if a node is totally destroyed then data can be lost.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The protocol is initiated by the coordinator after the last step of the transaction has been reached.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The participants then respond with an agreement message or an abort message depending on whether the transaction has been processed successfully at the participant.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The participants execute the transaction up to the point where they will be asked to commit.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] They each write an entry to their undo log and an entry to their redo log.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] (participant votes No to commit), if the participant experiences a failure that will make it impossible to commit.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Each participant completes the operation, and releases all the locks and resources held during the transaction.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Each participant sends an acknowledgement to the coordinator.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The coordinator completes the transaction when all acknowledgements have been received.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Each participant undoes the transaction using the undo log, and releases the resources and locks held during the transaction.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The coordinator undoes the transaction when all acknowledgements have been received.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] An * next to the record type means that the record is forced to stable storage.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] If the coordinator fails permanently, some participants will never resolve their transactions: After a participant has sent an agreement message as a response to the commit-request message from the coordinator, it will block until a commit or rollback is received.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] A two-phase commit protocol cannot dependably recover from a failure of both the coordinator and a cohort member during the commit phase.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] If only the coordinator had failed, and no cohort members had received a commit message, it could safely be inferred that no commit had happened.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] If, however, both the coordinator and a cohort member failed, it is possible that the failed cohort member was the first to be notified, and had actually done the commit.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Even if a new coordinator is selected, it cannot confidently proceed with the operation until it has received an agreement from all cohort members, and hence must block until all cohort members respond.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] In many cases the 2PC protocol is distributed in a computer network.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The databases involved with a distributed transaction, the participants, both the coordinator and participants, register to close TMs (typically residing on respective same network nodes as the participants) for terminating that transaction using 2PC.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Each distributed transaction has an ad hoc set of TMs, the TMs to which the transaction participants register.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] A leader, the coordinator TM, exists for each transaction to coordinate 2PC for it, typically the TM of the coordinator database.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] However, the coordinator role can be transferred to another TM for performance or reliability reasons.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Rather than exchanging 2PC messages among themselves, the participants exchange the messages with their respective TMs.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The relevant TMs communicate among themselves to execute the 2PC protocol schema above, "representing" the respective participants, for terminating that transaction.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] With this architecture the protocol is fully distributed (does not need any central processing component or data structure), and scales up with number of network nodes (network size) effectively.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] This common architecture is also effective for the distribution of other atomic commitment protocols besides 2PC, since all such protocols use the same voting mechanism and outcome propagation to protocol participants.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Database research has been done on ways to get most of the benefits of the two-phase commit protocol while reducing costs by protocol optimizations and protocol operations saving under certain system's behavior assumptions.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Presumed abort or Presumed commit are common such optimizations.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] An assumption about the outcome of transactions, either commit, or abort, can save both messages and logging operations by the participants during the 2PC protocol's execution.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] For example, when presumed abort, if during system recovery from failure no logged evidence for commit of some transaction is found by the recovery procedure, then it assumes that the transaction has been aborted, and acts accordingly.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] This means that it does not matter if aborts are logged at all, and such logging can be saved under this assumption.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Typically a penalty of additional operations is paid during recovery from failure, depending on optimization type.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Thus the best variant of optimization, if any, is chosen according to failure and transaction outcome statistics.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The Tree 2PC protocol (also called Nested 2PC, or Recursive 2PC) is a common variant of 2PC in a computer network, which better utilizes the underlying communication infrastructure.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The participants in a distributed transaction are typically invoked in an order which defines a tree structure, the invocation tree, where the participants are the nodes and the edges are the invocations (communication links).
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The same tree is commonly utilized to complete the transaction by a 2PC protocol, but also another communication tree can be utilized for this, in principle.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] In a tree 2PC the coordinator is considered the root ("top") of a communication tree (inverted tree), while the participants are the other nodes.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The coordinator can be the node that originated the transaction (invoked recursively (transitively) the other participants), but also another node in the same tree can take the coordinator role instead.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The Dynamic two-phase commit (Dynamic two-phase commitment, D2PC) protocol is a variant of Tree 2PC with no predetermined coordinator.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] It subsumes several optimizations that have been proposed earlier.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] Agreement messages (Yes votes) start to propagate from all the leaves, each leaf when completing its tasks on behalf of the transaction (becoming ready).
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] An intermediate (non leaf) node sends ready when an agreement message to the last (single) neighboring node from which agreement message has not yet been received.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] The coordinator is determined dynamically by racing agreement messages over the transaction tree, at the place where they collide.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] They collide either at a transaction tree node, to be the coordinator, or on a tree edge.
[src:gcp-spanner/two-phase-commit-protocol] In the latter case one of the two edge's nodes is elected as a coordinator (any node).
